for each GET request, the response may contain a Cache-Control, Expires,
ETag, and/or Last-Modified headers. if they exist in the response, the
client should keep track of each of these values for that URI and consult
them for any subsequent GET request to the same URI. that includes the case
you describe where you are sending POST requests to the same URI.

note that the POST may return a number of different &quot;success&quot; responses (200
OK + a body, 201 + Location Header, 202 Accepted + a body, 204 No Content,
3xx w/ a new URI, etc.). of course 4xx and 5xx responses are a possibility,
too. It is up to the client application to decide how to handle these
responses.

